<paragraph id="AECDDA9BAD99E20E1F3EDEA417126AAA" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">Occurs as terrestrial in lowland and montane rainforests.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F2247FB4BE6A5A0019599C7D7BCAAE4C" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="90486485565308D001667ABB933FC4F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9730FD3B65508B7449851FA280F93B57" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">
This species is easily recognizable by the subdimorphic leaves and orangish glands present on receptacle (
<bibRefCitation id="796F88A02F067A7616C44EB634B55DAA" author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 38" title="Taxonomy of ThelypterissubgenusSteiropteris, including Glaphyropteris (Pteridophyta)" volume="76" year="1980">Smith 1980</bibRefCitation>
). The closest species appears to be 
<taxonomicName id="DC2B43410D7E60A66761364480045477" authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="T." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. (Steiropteris) leprieurii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="leprieurii" subGenus="Steiropteris">T. (Steiropteris) leprieurii</taxonomicName>
(Hook.) R.M.Tryon, which can also present dimorphic fronds (
<bibRefCitation id="51268D82D525E92EE007108BA3C274BC" author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 38" title="Taxonomy of ThelypterissubgenusSteiropteris, including Glaphyropteris (Pteridophyta)" volume="76" year="1980">Smith 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
